b'' b'| b'| try this after xcreatewindow:' b'| b'| b'| b'| xsizehints-flags usposition ussize;\t/* or pposition psize b'| b'| xsetwmnormalhints (display, window, xsizehints);' b'| b'| b'| these hints tell the window manager that the position and size of the window' b'| are specified by the users and that the window manager should accept these' b'| values. if you use xsizehints-flags pposition psize, this tells the window' b'| manager that the values are prefered values of the program, not the user.' b"| i don't know a window manager that doesn't place the window like you prefer" b'| if you specify the position and size like above.' b'|' b"| sorry, but olwm and tvtwm don't do it. they place the title at that position" b'| and the window at a position below it.' b'' b'the reason they place their outside corner at the location you requested' b"is because that's what the icccm says they should do." b'' b'| this becomes a problem when you want a program to be able to save its current' b'| configuration and restore is later.' b'|' b'| currently, my solution is:' b'|' b'| \txcreatewindow(...);' b'| \txsetwmproperties(..);' b'| \txmapwindow(...);' b'| \txflush(...);' b'| \txmovewindow(...);' b'' b'this code will almost certainly break. calling xmapwindow and then' b'xflush does not guarantee that the window is visible and managed by the' b"window manager. even if this did work, there isn't a reliable way to" b'find out how much decoration the window manager placed around your' b"window, so you don't know how far to move it. and what if the window" b'manager refuses to move your window?' b'' b'--' 